{"title_page": "Charles Joseph Carter", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Charles Joseph Carter\n| spouse      = Corinne\n| image = Carter the Great Magician.jpg\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1874|6|14|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[New Castle, Pennsylvania]], [[United States]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1936|2|13|1874|6|14|mf=y}}\n| death_place = [[Bombay|India]]\n| occupation  = [[magic (illusion)|Magician]]\n}}\n\n'''Charles Joseph Carter''' (June 14, 1874 \u2013 February 13, 1936) was an American stage [[magic (illusion)|magician]], also known as '''Carter the Great'''.\n\n==Biography==\nHe was born on June 14, 1874 in [[New Castle, Pennsylvania]] and developed an interest in magic from a young age. Carter's first theatrical experience occurred at the Herzog's museum and Pat Harris' Masonic Temple in Baltimore at the age of 10, where he appeared as \"Master Charles Carter the Original Boy Magician\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://blog.mcmenamins.com/who-was-carter-the-great/|title=Who Was Carter the Great? \u2013 McMenamins Blog|website=blog.mcmenamins.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-24}}</ref> Due to stiff competition from the number of magic acts on the American stages at the time, Carter opted to pursue his career abroad, where he gained fame and notoriety.\n\nAmong the highlights of Carter's stage performances during his career were the classic \"sawing a woman in half\" illusion (an elaborate surgical-themed version with \"nurses\" in attendance), making a live elephant disappear and \"cheating the gallows\", where a shrouded Carter would vanish, just as he dropped at the end of a hangman's noose. He was also known for devising acts that were inspired by recent events that captured the public's imagination, such as the [[KV62|discovery of Tutankhamen's tomb]] in 1922 or [[John Dillinger]]'s famous jailbreak in 1934.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.themagicdetective.com/2011/07/carter-beats-devil-again.html|title=Carter Beats The Devil, Again|website=www.themagicdetective.com|language=en|access-date=2018-11-24}}</ref>\n\nIn 1894 he met his future wife, Corrine, whom he married and included in his show. A year later, his son, Lawrence, who would eventually take over the act after his death, was born.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAround the beginning of the century, Carter decided to settle down in Chicago along with his wife and son, his first major break from touring. During this time he tried to get a series of different business ventures up and running, such as an entertainment agency called The National Theatrical Exchange and his trade magazine called ''The Chicago Footlights,'' with various levels of success.<ref name=\":0\" /> During this time, he also enrolled in Law School, which he graduated from in 1905.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 1907 he set off again on a world tour that took him and his family to Australia, New Zealand, India, China, Sri Lanka, Egypt, Italy and beyond for three years. He would continue to tour the world with only short respites in the United States until 1917, completing seven world tours in this time.<ref name=\":0\" /> Because of his elaborate live shows, he had to travel everywhere with a lot of equipment, which at one point reached the weight of 31 tons.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Carter_the_Great.html?id=zcPXtgAACAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Carter the Great: Being a Detailed Account of Charles Joseph Carter and His Extraordinary Life as a Vagabond Illusionist who for Three Decades Circumnavigated the Globe with Thirty-one Tons of Magical Impedimenta|last=Caveney|first=Mike|date=1995|publisher=Mike Caveney's Magic Words|isbn=9780915181285|language=en}}</ref> According to some sources, it was this heavy equipment of his that lead to him being refused a place on the [[RMS Titanic]] during a return trip to the US in 1912.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nLooking for a break from his world touring magic show, Carter purchased the famous [[Martinka]] Magic Palace in 1917. Despite plans of opening Martinka shops all over the country, Carter soon discovered that he was losing money in the magic shop business and sold the Martinka two years later to a group of investors that included [[Harry Houdini]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.themagicdetective.com/2012/01/oldest-magic-shop-in-america.html|title=The Oldest Magic Shop in America|website=www.themagicdetective.com|language=en|access-date=2018-11-24}}</ref>  A famous anecdote states that he kept his lion, Monty, in the back room of the shop and when it would roar, the startled customers would run for the door.{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nIn 1921, he lost a fortune while filming ''The Lion\u2019s Bride'' in South Africa, a movie starring himself, that he had also written, produced, directed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://conjuringarts.org/2016/05/images-from-egyptian-hall-charles-carter/|title=Images from Egyptian Hall: Charles Carter {{!}} {{!}} Conjuring Arts|website=conjuringarts.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-24}}</ref> The film never made it to screen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.artefake.com/Charles-Joseph-CARTER.html|title=Charles Joseph CARTER - Artefake|website=www.artefake.com|language=fr|access-date=2018-11-24}}</ref>\n\nIn 1936, Charles Joseph Carter suffered a heart attack on his way to [[Mumbai|Bombay]], India. He was sent to the hospital and his son Larry took over the show. He died on February 13, 1936, aged 61 following a second heart attack. He is buried in the [[Calvary Cemetery (Queens, New York)|Calvary Cemetery]] in [[Queens|Queens, New York]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.findacadabra.com/index.php?fn=pois&f=show_details&id_poi=611|title=Carter the Great's Grave|website=Findacadabra - Discover the magic around you|access-date=2018-11-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FOHgDAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Resting Places: The Burial Sites of More Than 14,000 Famous Persons, 3d ed.|last=Wilson|first=Scott|date=2016-08-19|publisher=McFarland|isbn=9781476625997|location=Jefferson, NC|pages=121|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nCarter's home in San Francisco was rented by the [[Sumitomo Bank]] of California in the 1980s-90s and used as a residence for the Bank's President. Carter used to put on shows in the basement and people still discover occult references in the stained glass windows. The house is in the Seacliff District of San Francisco near the Pacific Ocean. It is sometimes mistakenly referred to as the \"Houdini Mansion\". It is now used as a foreign consulate.\n\nFollowing Charles Carter's death from a heart attack in 1936, his son Larry Carter took over as Carter the Great.\n\nA variety of vintage posters, advertising his shows, are on display at the [[House on the Rock]] in Wisconsin.\n\nIt is commonly believed that the character 'Maxwell' from the video game 'Don't Starve' was inspired by Carter because of his connections to magic and his relation to the city of San Francisco.\n\nA highly fictionalized account of his life can be found in ''[[Carter Beats the Devil]]'' ({{ISBN|0-7868-8632-3}}) by [[Glen David Gold]]. The rights to the novel were purchased in 2002 by [[Paramount Pictures|Paramount]], with Tom Cruise planning to star and produce, but the film has since been stuck in [[production hell]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/21-jump-street-directors-carter-beats-devil-332445|title='21 Jump Street' Directors in Talks for 'Carter Beats the Devil' (Exclusive)|last=Kit|first=Borys|date=3 June 2012|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2018-11-24|language=en}}</ref> Warner Bros. currently hold the rights to a Carter Beats the Devil film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/jump-st-carter-beats-devil/|title=From Jump St To Carter Beats The Devil?|last=White|first=James|date=4 June 2012|website=Empire|language=en|access-date=2018-11-24}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline - touring dates==\n;1906\n*September 15\u201321      : [[Decatur, Illinois]]\n*September 27 - Oct 3 : [[Cleveland, Ohio]]\n*October 4 - ?        : [[Cincinnati, Ohio]]\n*October 28 - ?       : [[Holland, Michigan]]\n*November 8 - ?       : [[Chicago Heights, Illinois]]\n*November 19 - ?      : [[Fairmount, Indiana]]\n*November 30 - ?      : [[Tecumseh, Michigan]]\n\n;1907\n\n;1912\n*December 25          : [[Terre Haute, Indiana]]\n\n;1917\n* March 15            : [[New York City]] (Moss' Jefferson Theatre)\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n*''Carter the Great'', by Mike Caveney (1995) Magic Words\n*''[[Carter Beats the Devil]]'', by [[Glen David Gold]] (fictional version of Carter's life)\n*\"The Carter Scrapbook\", by Gary R. Frank and Phil Temple (1992)\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050204132145/http://www.magicgallery.com/Carter.htm Carter-related memorabilia]\n*[http://www.martinka.com/martinka/auction/APSearch.asp?CMD=SEARCH&SearchFor=Carter&SearchDesc=Y&SearchClosed=Y Carter-related memorabilia]\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carter, Charles Joseph}}\n[[Category:1874 births]]\n[[Category:1936 deaths]]\n[[Category:American magicians]]\n[[Category:People from New Castle, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Vaudeville performers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Charles Joseph Carter\n| spouse      = Corinne\n| image = Carter the Great Magician.jpg\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1874|6|14|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[New Castle, Pennsylvania]], [[United States]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1936|2|13|1874|6|14|mf=y}}\n| death_place = [[Bombay|India]]\n| occupation  = [[magic (illusion)|Magician]]\n}}\n\n'''Charles Joseph Carter''' (June 14, 1874 \u2013 February 13, 1936) was an American stage [[magic (illusion)|magician]], also known as '''Carter the Great'''.\n\n==Biography==\nHe was born on June 14, 1874 in [[New Castle, Pennsylvania]] and developed an interest in magi